\section{Ejercicio 10}\label{ejercicio-10}

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, opacityback=0, coltitle=black, toprule=.15mm, breakable, arc=.35mm, left=2mm, bottomrule=.15mm, bottomtitle=1mm, colframe=quarto-callout-note-color-frame, leftrule=.75mm, rightrule=.15mm, colback=white, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-note-color!10!white, titlerule=0mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-note-color}{\faInfo}\hspace{0.5em}{Instrucción}, toptitle=1mm]

En el capítulo de análisis funcional complete las demostraciones de los
teoremas 2, 4, 5, 14, 16 y de los ejemplos 3, 5.

\end{tcolorbox}

\subsection{Solución}\label{soluciuxf3n-8}

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, opacityback=0, coltitle=black, toprule=.15mm, breakable, arc=.35mm, left=2mm, bottomrule=.15mm, bottomtitle=1mm, colframe=quarto-callout-tip-color-frame, leftrule=.75mm, rightrule=.15mm, colback=white, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-tip-color!10!white, titlerule=0mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-tip-color}{\faLightbulb}\hspace{0.5em}{Teorema 2}, toptitle=1mm]

En un espacio vectorial de dimensión finita todas las normas son
equivalentes.

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, opacityback=0, coltitle=black, toprule=.15mm, breakable, arc=.35mm, left=2mm, bottomrule=.15mm, bottomtitle=1mm, colframe=quarto-callout-caution-color-frame, leftrule=.75mm, rightrule=.15mm, colback=white, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-caution-color!10!white, titlerule=0mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-caution-color}{\faFire}\hspace{0.5em}{Prueba}, toptitle=1mm]

\(\blacksquare\)

\end{tcolorbox}

\end{tcolorbox}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, opacityback=0, coltitle=black, toprule=.15mm, breakable, arc=.35mm, left=2mm, bottomrule=.15mm, bottomtitle=1mm, colframe=quarto-callout-tip-color-frame, leftrule=.75mm, rightrule=.15mm, colback=white, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-tip-color!10!white, titlerule=0mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-tip-color}{\faLightbulb}\hspace{0.5em}{Teorema 4}, toptitle=1mm]

Para todo producto interno se tiene la desigualdad de Cauchy--Schwarz:

\[|\langle x, y \rangle|^2 \leq \langle x, x \rangle \langle y, y \rangle,\]

para todo \(x, y \in X\), además se tiene igualdad si para todo \(x, y\)
son linealmente dependientes.

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, opacityback=0, coltitle=black, toprule=.15mm, breakable, arc=.35mm, left=2mm, bottomrule=.15mm, bottomtitle=1mm, colframe=quarto-callout-caution-color-frame, leftrule=.75mm, rightrule=.15mm, colback=white, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-caution-color!10!white, titlerule=0mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-caution-color}{\faFire}\hspace{0.5em}{Prueba}, toptitle=1mm]

Si \(x = 0\) la desigualdad es trivial. Si \(x \neq 0\), tome

\[z = y - \frac{\langle y, x \rangle}{\|x\|^2} x,\]

luego es claro que \(\langle z, x \rangle = 0\) y que:

\[
0 \leq \|z\|^2 
= \left\langle y - \frac{\langle y, x \rangle}{\|x\|^2}x , \, y - \frac{\langle y, x \rangle}{\|x\|^2}x \right\rangle
= \langle y, y \rangle - \frac{\langle y, x \rangle \langle x, y \rangle}{\|x\|^2}
= \|y\|^2 - \frac{|\langle x, y \rangle|^2}{\|x\|^2}.
\]

De donde se tiene la desigualdad. Además se tiene igualdad si para todo
\(x, y\) son linealmente dependientes (ejercicio).

\(\blacksquare\)

\end{tcolorbox}

\end{tcolorbox}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, opacityback=0, coltitle=black, toprule=.15mm, breakable, arc=.35mm, left=2mm, bottomrule=.15mm, bottomtitle=1mm, colframe=quarto-callout-tip-color-frame, leftrule=.75mm, rightrule=.15mm, colback=white, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-tip-color!10!white, titlerule=0mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-tip-color}{\faLightbulb}\hspace{0.5em}{Teorema 5}, toptitle=1mm]

Sea \(X\) un espacio vectorial complejo (o real). Entonces la función

\[
\|x\| := \langle x, x \rangle^{1/2}
\]

define una norma en \(X\), es decir un espacio pre--Hilbert es siempre
un espacio normado.

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, opacityback=0, coltitle=black, toprule=.15mm, breakable, arc=.35mm, left=2mm, bottomrule=.15mm, bottomtitle=1mm, colframe=quarto-callout-caution-color-frame, leftrule=.75mm, rightrule=.15mm, colback=white, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-caution-color!10!white, titlerule=0mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-caution-color}{\faFire}\hspace{0.5em}{Prueba}, toptitle=1mm]

Ejercicio (use la desigualdad de Cauchy--Schwarz para probar la
desigualdad triangular).

\(\blacksquare\)

\end{tcolorbox}

\end{tcolorbox}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, opacityback=0, coltitle=black, toprule=.15mm, breakable, arc=.35mm, left=2mm, bottomrule=.15mm, bottomtitle=1mm, colframe=quarto-callout-tip-color-frame, leftrule=.75mm, rightrule=.15mm, colback=white, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-tip-color!10!white, titlerule=0mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-tip-color}{\faLightbulb}\hspace{0.5em}{Teorema 14}, toptitle=1mm]

Sea \(U\) un subespacio vectorial de un espacio de pre--Hilbert \(X\).\\
Un elemento \(v\) es la mejor aproximación a \(w \in X\) con respecto a
\(U\) si y solo si:

\[
\langle w - v, u \rangle = 0 \quad \forall u \in U.
\]

Es decir, si y solamente si \(w - v \perp U\). Además, para cada
\(w \in X\) existe a lo más una única mejor aproximación con respecto a
\(U\).

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, opacityback=0, coltitle=black, toprule=.15mm, breakable, arc=.35mm, left=2mm, bottomrule=.15mm, bottomtitle=1mm, colframe=quarto-callout-caution-color-frame, leftrule=.75mm, rightrule=.15mm, colback=white, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-caution-color!10!white, titlerule=0mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-caution-color}{\faFire}\hspace{0.5em}{Prueba}, toptitle=1mm]

(Ejercicio)

\(\blacksquare\)

\end{tcolorbox}

\end{tcolorbox}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, opacityback=0, coltitle=black, toprule=.15mm, breakable, arc=.35mm, left=2mm, bottomrule=.15mm, bottomtitle=1mm, colframe=quarto-callout-tip-color-frame, leftrule=.75mm, rightrule=.15mm, colback=white, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-tip-color!10!white, titlerule=0mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-tip-color}{\faLightbulb}\hspace{0.5em}{Teorema 16}, toptitle=1mm]

Sea \(U\) un subespacio vectorial completo de un espacio pre--Hilbert
\(X\).\\
Entonces para cada elemento \(w \in X\) existe una única mejor
aproximación con respecto a \(U\).

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  El operador \(P : X \to U\) que le asigna a \(w \in X\) su mejor
  aproximación es un operador lineal acotado con las siguientes
  propiedades:
\end{itemize}

\[
P^2 = P \quad \text{y} \quad \|P\| = 1.
\]

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Este operador se conoce como la \textbf{proyección ortogonal} de \(X\)
  sobre \(U\).
\end{itemize}

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, opacityback=0, coltitle=black, toprule=.15mm, breakable, arc=.35mm, left=2mm, bottomrule=.15mm, bottomtitle=1mm, colframe=quarto-callout-caution-color-frame, leftrule=.75mm, rightrule=.15mm, colback=white, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-caution-color!10!white, titlerule=0mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-caution-color}{\faFire}\hspace{0.5em}{Prueba}, toptitle=1mm]

(Ejercicio)

\(\blacksquare\)

\end{tcolorbox}

\end{tcolorbox}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, opacityback=0, coltitle=black, toprule=.15mm, breakable, arc=.35mm, left=2mm, bottomrule=.15mm, bottomtitle=1mm, colframe=quarto-callout-tip-color-frame, leftrule=.75mm, rightrule=.15mm, colback=white, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-tip-color!10!white, titlerule=0mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-tip-color}{\faLightbulb}\hspace{0.5em}{Ejemplo 3}, toptitle=1mm]

El espacio vectorial \(C[a,b]\) provisto con la norma

\[
\|f\|_\infty := \max_{x \in [a,b]} |f(x)|
\]

es un espacio de Banach.

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, opacityback=0, coltitle=black, toprule=.15mm, breakable, arc=.35mm, left=2mm, bottomrule=.15mm, bottomtitle=1mm, colframe=quarto-callout-caution-color-frame, leftrule=.75mm, rightrule=.15mm, colback=white, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-caution-color!10!white, titlerule=0mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-caution-color}{\faFire}\hspace{0.5em}{Prueba}, toptitle=1mm]

(Ejercicio)

\(\blacksquare\)

\end{tcolorbox}

\end{tcolorbox}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, opacityback=0, coltitle=black, toprule=.15mm, breakable, arc=.35mm, left=2mm, bottomrule=.15mm, bottomtitle=1mm, colframe=quarto-callout-tip-color-frame, leftrule=.75mm, rightrule=.15mm, colback=white, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-tip-color!10!white, titlerule=0mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-tip-color}{\faLightbulb}\hspace{0.5em}{Ejemplo 5}, toptitle=1mm]

El espacio vectorial \(C[a,b]\) provisto con la norma \(L_2\):

\[
\|f\|_1 := \left( \int_a^b |f(x)|^2 dx \right)^2
\]

NO es un espacio de Banach.

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, opacityback=0, coltitle=black, toprule=.15mm, breakable, arc=.35mm, left=2mm, bottomrule=.15mm, bottomtitle=1mm, colframe=quarto-callout-caution-color-frame, leftrule=.75mm, rightrule=.15mm, colback=white, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-caution-color!10!white, titlerule=0mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-caution-color}{\faFire}\hspace{0.5em}{Prueba}, toptitle=1mm]

Ejercicio (sug. use la misma sucesión del ejemplo 4).

\(\blacksquare\)

\end{tcolorbox}

\end{tcolorbox}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\section{Ejercicio 11}\label{ejercicio-11}

